# Data and restore security

## Untrusted input

- Files and JSON passed into restore / migration / import paths must be treated as hostile: validate shapes, types, and allowed value ranges before use.
- Reject or clamp oversized payloads (element counts, string lengths, nesting) where the codebase supports it; prefer failing closed for clearly invalid data.

## No code execution from data

- Never `eval`, `new Function`, or dynamic `import()` based on values from saved files or API responses in this layer.

## Compatibility vs safety

- Preserve backward compatibility with existing `.excalidraw` formats, but do not relax validation solely to accept malformed data; fix forward with explicit migration steps when needed.

## Protected files

- Changes to critical paths (e.g. `restore.ts` per project rules) require full test runs and careful review — see `.cursor/rules/do-not-touch.mdc`.

## Logging

- Do not log full user documents or PII by default in restore/debug paths.

## Disclose in chat

When this rule materially guides your response or edits, state in the Cursor chat that you applied it — mention `.cursor/rules/security-data-restore.mdc` (one short line is enough).

## How to verify

- Grep `packages/excalidraw/data` for `eval`, `new Function`, and dynamic `import(` driven by parsed file content; there should be none.
- Run `yarn test:update` (or the full suite) after changing restore/migration/import paths; exercise import/restore flows manually when validation logic changes.
